# What is a Drug (2) 
  
**Definition**  
* A substance used as a medication or in the preparation of medication.  
* According to the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act  
(1) a substance recognized in an official pharmacopoeia or formulary  
(2) a substance intended for use in the diagnosis, cure, mitigation, treatment, or prevention of disease  
(3) a substance other than food intended to affect the structure or function of the body  
* Something and often an illegal substance that causes addiction, habituation, or a marked change in consciousness  
  
**Trivial names and Structural Formulas**  
* nicotine  
* procaine  
* morphine  
* Botulinum toxin  

**This session’s drugs exemplify the concepts in “Drugs and the Brain”**  
* Drugs Activate (nicotine) and block (procaine) ion channels  
* Drugs act on G protein pathways (morphine)  
* Drugs activate genes (nicotine, morphine)  
* Protein drugs may become more useful for neuroscience diseases (botulinum toxin)  
* Not treated in this session: Drugs act on neurotransmitter transporters  
* Botulinum toxin does not get into the brain. It actually works in the peripheral nervous system, at the nerve muscle synapse. That's an important distinction.  
  
**Atomic-scale Structures**  
PubChem Database  
* [nicotine](http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?cid=89594&loc=ec_rcs)  
:* has a conjugated and aromatic ring (the double bonds)  
:* they are delocalized, hybridized 
* [procaine](http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?cid=4914&loc=ec_rcs) 
* [morphine](http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?cid=5288826&loc=ec_rcs) 
