# Botulinum Toxin (4)  
* Botulinum toxin is made by *Clostridium botulinum*, an anaerobic bacterium.  
* Botulinum toxin is fatal in extremely low quantities (~ 1 molecule per synapse), because it paralyzes muscles. 10^-8 grams kills a mouse. The paralysis occurs because presynaptic
terminals cannot release transmitter.  
* The bacterium synthesizes botulinum toxin as a single protein chain, then cleaves the chain.  
* The two portions are still held together by a disulphide bond between two cysteine residues.  
* The light chain and the heavy chain held together.  
* The two chains enter into neurons and other cells.  
* When they are inside neurons, there is a reducing environment which reduces the disulphide bond.  
* The light chain and the heavy chain separate.  
* The light chain acts as an enzyme. 
* Many diseases and discomforts are caused by excess muscle activity.  
* Botulinum toxin, injected in minute quantities, blocks this excess activity and gives relief from squint and spasm.  
* Botulinum toxin also decreases frown lines (Botox®).  
  
**What are some possible new therapeutic uses for botulinum toxin?**  
http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=botulinum%20toxin  
Gastroparesis  
Hemiplegia  
Blepharospasm  
Skew deviation  
glabellar lines  
cervical myelopathy  
neurogenic detrusor overactivity  
Tourette syndrome  



