# Introduction to mammalian brains. Neuronal circuits, neurons, and synapses (7)   
 
**ANATOMY**  
  
The Central Nervous System (CNS) consists of two major parts the Brain at the top and the Spinal Cord which protrudes from the brain.  
  
Terminolgy  
  
front - rostral direction  
  
back - caudal direction  
  
posterior - dorsal  
  
anterior - ventral  
  
Important concept is that specific brain regions are the seats of specific functions.  
  
  
$$\begin{array}{|c|c|}  
REGION & FUNCTION \\\ \hline 
Motor\ Cortex\ (top\ just\ forward\ of\ central\ sulcus) & Movement \\\ \hline
Sensory\ Cortex\ (just\ back\ of\ central\ sulcus)& Sensation \\\ \hline
Visual\ Cortex\ (occipital\ lobe\ in\ caudal\ part\ of\ brain) & Sight \\\ \hline
Pre-frontal\ Cortex\ (rostral\ part\ of\ the\ brain)& Partial\ function\ of\ judgement\ and\ higher\ neural\ function \\\ \hline
Hippocampus & Memory\ is\ laid\ down\ initially \\\ \hline
Basal\ Ganglia\ and\ to\ some\ extent\ Cerebellum & Motor\ Coordination \\\ \hline
The\ Reward\ Pathway\ (important\ part\ of\ Drugs\ and\ the\ Brain) & Nicotine,\ Dopamine\ and\ other\ reward\ transmitters\ play\ a\ role \\\  
\end{array}$$  
  
  
**SIMPLE CIRCUIT**  
  
EG Jamming finger in a door.  
  
This involves the periphery, the spinal cord and the brain.  
  
Pain sensations travel towards the Brain through the Nerve Roots, into the Spinal Cord where they synapse onto neurons which then project in an ascending fashion towards the brain.  Most sensory messages synapse in the Thalamus then go to the Sensory Cortex.  Then we decide to move from the pain.  We go more to the Motor Cortex back down to the Thalamus and then a descending pathway back to the Spinal Cord to a motor neuron which tells the finger and the hand to move out of the way.  
  
This simple pathway involves Neurons, Synapses and a Loop.  
  
**SPINAL REFLEXES**

EG Knee Jerk is simpler.  
  
They involve just 2 neurons.  
  
A special type of muscle fiber(the spindle) is hit with a tendon hammer which stretches the tendon. The Spindle goes into the CNS, into the spinal cord through the dorsal root ganglion, synapses onto motor neurons which contract the muscle and make the leg jerk up. There is an additional pathway which inhibits the opposing flexor muscles and the reflex knee jerk.   
  
This reflex acts almost completely on its own with no desetting control from the brain.  Interestingly the sensory neurons act like strain gauges wrapped around these special muscle fibers.  
  
So again we have the involvement of a sensory organ, a projection into the CNS, some processing and then a motor projection back out to the muscles.  
  
**PARTS OF TWO NEURONS (Refer to relevant slides mini lecture 7)**
  
From left to right.  Pre Synaptic Neuron on the right and the Post Synaptic Neuron on the left.  All major parts are labelled.  The Myelin Sheath around the Axon makes the nerve conduct faster.  
  
When one neuron contacts another, we find the synapse which is the point of information processing in the CNS.  It is a little Chemical hop whereas the nerve impulse is Electrical while travelling within the neuron.  It changes to chemistry to jump across the synapse and then it ususally changes back to electricity again and flows on its way.  
  
The Neuron and Synaptic statistics for adult, infant and fetal brains are presented again and are documented on the slides.    
  
It was not until the Electron Microscope was invented in the 1940s that the synapse was identified.  The first electron micro-graphs clearly showed the gap between the pre and post synaptic neurons.  
  
We have seen that chemistry is a language of the brain eg at synapses.  In a very simple view of the synapse we see:  
  
< transmitter molecules in vescicles in the presynaptic terminal they are embedded in the cytosol (intracellular environment)  
< the synaptic cleft separates the pre and post synaptic cells. It's about 500 angstroms wide.    
< In the post synaptic dendrite membrane are receptors which are a large part of Drugs and the Brain.  
< The receptors usually transduce little chemical hops into electricity and the nerve impulse begins again after a great deal of processing and summation by many receptors at many places on the post synaptic cell.  
  
Next time we'll talk about electricity as the language of the brain.  
  
