# Origin of the Resting Potential (9)  
* Simply reverse the ratio of sodium and potassium inside and outside cells.  
* Outside cells, in the extra cellular solution, most organisms have a high concentration of sodium ions.  
* Inside, most organisms have a high concentration of potassium ions.  
* I'll remind you that when you put sodium chloride, salt or KCl, in solution, sodium chloride dissolves and the sodium and chloride ions separate from each other, and each becomes hydrated by water molecules but retains their charge.  
* We have high internal potassium, low internal sodium, and their sums are the same, sodium plus chloride, so that we actually keep the osmotic pressure the same inside and outside the cells and the cells don't burst.  
  
**Typical extracellular and cytosolic ion concentrations (mammalian cell)**  
  
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
Major\ monovalent\ ions & Extracellular & Intracellular (cytosol) \\\ \hline
Na+ & 145\ mM & 15\ mM \\\ 
K+ & 4\ mM & 150\ mM \\\
Cl- & 110\ mM & 10\ mM \\\ \hline
\end{array}  
  
  
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
Major\ divalent\ ions & Extracellular & Intracellular (cytosol) \\\ \hline
Ca2+ & 2\ mM & 15\ 10^{-8}\ mM \\\ 
Mg2+ & 2\ mM & 0.5\ mM \\\
Cl- & 110\ mM & 10\ mM \\\ \hline
\end{array}  
  
  
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
Other\ ions & Extracellular & Intracellular (cytosol) \\\ \hline
Pi-2 & 2\ mM & 40\ mM \\\ 
H+ & 10^{-7}\ mM & 10^{-7}\ mM \\\
Protein\ (not\ an\ ion) & 0.2\ mM & 4\ mM \\\ \hline
\end{array}  
  
  
**Converting a concentration gradient to an electrical potential**  
* Create permeability to one ionic species (K+)  
* Potassium ions diffuse down their chemical gradient from the inside to the outside of the cell.  
* This causes a lost positive charge inside the cell, this leads to a net, negative interior potential, and so, this is the origin of the resting potential.  

**Deriving the Nernst Potential (Chemistry Units)**  
* The Nernst potential means that the energy of discharging the concentration gradient for potassium ions balances the energy of moving the potassium ions back through the potential difference.  
  
**Neurons are not Equilibrium Systems**  
* Several types of channels of channels are open at once.
* To analyze resting potentials under these circumstances, we’ll switch to electrical calculations.  
  
**Atomic-scale structure of (bacterial) Na+ channels**  
* A voltage-gated sodium channel has 4 sub-units (4 different colors), and if we magnify the central axis of the channel, we see the space through which sodium ions can permeate.  
* We expect to see a symmetrical or pseudosymmetric structure with the permeation pathway on the axis.  
* The keypoint here is that because ions can diffuse rather easily through the channel and we have a conducting pathway, this means that an individual channel acts very much like a conductor.  
* A conductor and a resistor are the same thing. Conductance is the inverse of resistance. Conductance is one over the resistance.  
  
---  
  
# Electrical Aspects of Ion Channels (10)  
**The miniature single-channel conductors add in parallel**  
* Cells have tens or hundreds, or thousands, or hundreds of thousands of individual single molecule potassium channels in parallel.  
* Each one of them has a switch, which says whether the channel is active or not active.  * Each one of them has its battery, which is its Nernst potential.  
* There is a macroscopic conductance (G), which is the sum of all of the microscopic conductances (gamma).  
* G is the sum of all of the little gammas who's switches allow the channel to open.  
* Because a large number of individual channels act some in parallel if their switches allow them too, we have a variable total conductance GNA in series with the Nernst potential for sodium, and a variable potassium conductance in series with a Nernst potential for potassium.  
* Conservation of charge or Kirchoff's Current Law: a charge that flows in through a sodium channel, must be balanced by flowing out through a potassium channel.  
  
**The membrane potential at steady state**  
* It is not an equilibrium because the cell is pumping all of those ions back.  
* The resting potential is a weighted sum of the Nernst potential for potassium times its
conductance plus the Nernst potential for sodium times it's conductance.  
* At rest, mostly potassium channels are open. So, the potassium terms dominate and we
have a resting potential which is very near EK (the resting potential for potassium).  
* If sodium channels are open, then we have a membrane potential that becomes nearer to the sodium Nernst potential.  
* This is how we can change the voltage across a biological membrane, how nature changes the voltage across a biological membrane with drugs that open ion channels.  
  
**Two Major Roles for Ion Channels in Drugs and the Brain**  
* At synapses, we have a neurotransmitter or an agonist changing ion channels from closed to open in changing the potential across the cell.  
* The importance of changing the potential across the cell is that this changes the frequency of action potentials.  
* In addition, at axons and cell bodies drugs can change the equilibrium between closed and open voltage gated channels.    
  
